Jenna Etheridge, News24President Jacob Zuma and Speaker Baleka Mbete. (Felix Dlangamandla/Foto24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town &ndash; ANC national chairperson Baleka Mbete on Tuesday condemned suggestions that she was behind items bearing her image and the words &ldquo;incoming president&rdquo;.An outraged Mbete denied any involvement in the production or circulation of the items and electronic posters, saying they were &ldquo;mischievous tactics&rdquo; designed to tarnish her reputation in the eyes of ANC members and society.&ldquo;Such acts are clearly the work of so-called lobbyists seeking to erode unity within the organisation and divide the movement by pitting comrade against comrade,&rdquo; said Mbete.A poster emerged on digital platforms showing a cap and T-shirt with pictures of Mbete&rsquo;s face, the ANC logo and the words &ldquo;BM17, Baleka Mbete, Incoming President&rdquo;.The ANC will hold its elective conference in December.The poster had the format of a marketing strategy, listing the words, &ldquo;online campaign, interactive media, social media marketing, competitions, giveaways, guerilla [sic] marketing and clothing apparel&rdquo;.ANC spokesperson Zizi Kodwa said Mbete&rsquo;s position was in line with the ruling party&rsquo;s stated directive that &ldquo;members of the ANC, its structures and league must desist from divisive behaviour which undermine the unity and cohesion of the ANC towards the 54th National Conference and beyond&rdquo;.Mbete said those behind the campaign should stop using her name. 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.